description:
Methods for folate analysis include bioassays, LC, ligand-binding, and immunoassay. Folate analysis is complicated by the multiple metabolic forms present in biological samples, variable -glutamyl polymer lenghts of 2 to 12, and instability. 
Traditional microbiological techniques can be modified to the microplate procedures.&nbsp; 
Various biospecific methods using ligand binding have been developed for folate analysis of clinical samples (blood and serum). Methods based upon the specific interaction of antibody with its antigen include radioimmunoassay and enzyme-linked immunoabsorbent assay (ELISA). Assays using naturally occuring vitamin binding proteins with isotope labels or enzyme labels include radio-labeled protein binding assays based on isotope dillution procedures and enzyme protein binding assays.&nbsp; 
HPLC methods are another techniques for folate determination, mainly in blood and serum. In these methods fluorescent, photodiode array, UV, electrochemical and mass spectometry detectors are used. Although the fluorescent and electrochemical detectors are very sensitive, it is not possible to use them for determination of all folate derivates. UV spectometry is generally apllied for all folate derivatives, but it is not sensitive enough to quantify low concentrations of folates in the samples.&nbsp; 
Before HPLC determination, folates are extracted from materials with amylase, protease and conjugase and purified by affinity chromatography and concentrated. All analytical steps including quantification must be performed on one day under subdued light to reduce folate degradation.

